  "prompt": "What are Some interesting facts of Langar at golden temple?",
  "response": "Langar at the Golden Temple (Harmandir Sahib) in Amritsar, Punjab, is one of the most iconic and inspiring examples of community service in the world. Here are some interesting facts about it:\n\n1. **Free for All**: The Langar at the Golden Temple is open to everyone, regardless of religion, caste, gender, or social status. It serves as a symbol of equality and inclusivity.\n\n2. **Massive Scale**: Every day, the Langar feeds an estimated 50,000 to 100,000 people. On special occasions or festivals, this number can rise to over 200,000.\n\n3. **24/7 Service**: The Langar operates 24 hours a day, 365 days a year, ensuring that no one leaves the Golden Temple hungry.\n\n4. **Volunteer-Powered**: Everything at the Langar is run by volunteers (sevadars) who selflessly serve food, clean utensils, and manage the kitchen. Thousands of volunteers contribute daily.\n\n5. **Simple Yet Nutritious Meal**: The Langar serves a vegetarian meal, typically consisting of dal (lentils), roti (flatbread), rice, and a vegetable dish, along with a sweet like kheer (rice pudding). The food is simple but highly nutritious.\n\n6. **Community Cooking**: The kitchen at the Golden Temple is massive and uses industrial-sized equipment. For example, cauldrons that can cook up to 1,000 kg of dal at a time are used.\n\n7. **On-Site Farming**: Some of the ingredients used in the Langar are grown on farms owned by the Golden Temple. This ensures fresh and organic produce.\n\n8. **No Wastage**: Every effort is made to ensure no food is wasted. Leftover food is either distributed to those in need or used for animal feed.\n\n9. **Hygiene and Cleanliness**: The Langar maintains strict hygiene standards. Volunteers clean utensils thoroughly in a dedicated area, and the kitchen is spotless.\n\n10. **History of Service**: The tradition of Langar was established by Guru Nanak, the founder of Sikhism, and has been practiced for over 500 years. The Golden Temple\u2019s Langar has been serving meals since its inception in 1604.\n\n11. **Unity in Sitting**: Everyone sits on the floor in rows (pangat), signifying equality. There is no concept of VIP treatment; all are equal in the eyes of the Guru.\n\n12. **Largest Free Kitchen in the World**: The Langar at the Golden Temple is often referred to as the largest free kitchen in the world, serving millions of meals annually.\n\n13. **Global Inspiration**: The Langar\u2019s model of selfless service and community feeding has inspired similar initiatives worldwide.\n\nThe Langar at the Golden Temple is not just a meal but a profound spiritual experience that embodies the Sikh principles of seva (selfless service), equality, and compassion. It's a testament to the power of community and the spirit of giving.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
